<DOC><DOCNO> AP891002-0312 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1221EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-USX-OilReserves     10-02 0229</FIRST><SECOND>PM-USX-Oil Reserves,0235</SECOND><HEAD>USX Puts Oil Reserves on Block</HEAD><DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   USX Corp. said today it is offering to sellthe oil and natural gas reserves of its Texas Oil andamp; Gas Corp.subsidiary.   The oil and steel giant said it has retained the investmentbanking firm First Boston Corp. to handle the sale. The reservesare mainly located in Texas, Oklahoma, Arkansas, Louisiana,Colorado and Kansas.   USX, based in Pittsburgh, issued 133 million shares of stock in1986 to acquire Texas Oil andamp; Gas in a deal valued at around $3billion. USX has been disappointed by the company's earnings eversince. The parent has pinned its hopes for a turnaround at TexasOil andamp; Gas on the prospect of natural gas prices surging.   A sale is anticipated by year's end, said USX spokesman WilliamE. Keslar, who declined to say what value USX places on thereserves.   Texas Oil andamp; Gas has 1.2 trillion cubic feet of gas in reserve,about a quarter of the 3.5 trillion cubic feet held by the otherUSX subsidiary, Marathon Oil Co. Texas Oil andamp; Gas has 28 millionbarrels of oil, or 3 percent of Marathon's 766 million barrels.   The bulk of Texas Oil andamp; Gas' business is natural gas gathering,which would not be affected by the sale. The subsidiary also wouldretain its contract drilling business.</TEXT></DOC>